[AttributeUsage(AttributeTargets.Method, AllowMultiple = true, Inherited = true)]
public sealed class MemberDataAttribute : MemberDataAttributeBase, IDataAttribute

<AttributeUsage(AttributeTargets.Method, AllowMultiple:=True, Inherited:=True)>
Public NotInheritable Class MemberDataAttribute Inherits MemberDataAttributeBase Implements IDataAttribute

inheritedMembers.summary: Gets or sets the arguments passed to the member. Only supported for static methods.

Returns true if the data attribute wants to skip enumerating data during discovery. This will cause the theory to yield a single test case for all data, and the data discovery will be during test execution instead of discovery.
Gets or sets the type to retrieve the member from. If not set, then the member will be retrieved from the unit test class.
Returns the data to be used to test the theory.
Returns true if the data attribute supports enumeration during discovery; false otherwise. Data attributes with expensive computational costs and/or randomized data sets should return false.

Sets a value that determines whether the data rows provided by this data provider should be considered explicit or not. If true, then the data rows will all be considered explicit; if false, then the data rows will all be considered not explicit; if unset, then the data rows will inherit their explicitness from .
Gets a skip reason for all the data rows provided by this data provider. If not null, then all rows will be skipped with the given reason; if null, then the rows will inherit their skip reason from .
Gets the test display name for the test (replacing the default behavior, which would be to use , or falling back to generating display names based on and ).

Sets a value to determine if the data rows provided by this data provider should include a timeout (in milliseconds). If greater than zero, the data rows will have the given timeout; if zero or less, the data rows will not have a timeout; if unset, the data rows will inherit their timeout from .
Gets a set of traits for the associated data. The data is provided as an array of string values that are alternating keys and values (e.g., ["key1", "value1", "key2", "value2"]).
